1. how we register the character device driver

In the Linux Kernel, a character device driver must be registered with the kernel so the kernel knows that your driver handles a 
particular major/minor device number. Registration is typically done during the module initialization.

There are two common ways to register a character device driver:

1️⃣ Using register_chrdev() (Older / Simple Method)
static int major;
static int __init my_init(void)
{
    major = register_chrdev(0, "mychardev", &fops);
    printk("Major number = %d\n", major);
    return 0;
}

Parameters:
major – Major device number (0 for dynamic allocation)
name – Name of the device
fops – Pointer to file_operations structure

2️⃣ Using alloc_chrdev_region() + cdev (Modern Method ✅)
This is the recommended approach.

Steps:
Allocate device numbers
Initialize cdev structure
Add device to kernel

dev_t dev;
struct cdev my_cdev;
static int __init my_init(void)
{
    alloc_chrdev_region(&dev, 0, 1, "mychardev");
    cdev_init(&my_cdev, &fops);
    cdev_add(&my_cdev, dev, 1);
    printk("Major: %d Minor: %d\n", MAJOR(dev), MINOR(dev));
    return 0;
}

2. when the module are loaded into kernel linux

Linux modules are loaded dynamically using commands like insmod or modprobe. The module file (.ko) is inserted into kernel memory, 
dependencies are resolved, and the module initialization function registered with module_init() is executed.

When a module is loaded:
1️⃣ User runs insmod or modprobe
2️⃣ Kernel loads the .ko file into kernel memory
3️⃣ Kernel resolves symbol dependencies
4️⃣ Kernel executes module initialization function

3. what is the difference between insmod and modprobe

insmod loads a module directly, while modprobe loads the module along with its dependencies automatically.

insmod:
Loads a kernel module directly
Requires full .ko file
Does not handle dependencies

modprobe:
Loads module from /lib/modules
Automatically loads dependencies
Recommended command

What modprobe does internally:
Searches module in
/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/
Checks module dependencies
Loads required modules automatically
Inserts the requested module.

4. what is the use of __inti and __exit in linux module programming

In Linux kernel module programming, __init and __exit are macros used to mark initialization and cleanup functions of a kernel module.
They help the kernel optimize memory usage.

__init is used to mark the initialization function of a kernel module and its memory is freed after execution.
__exit is used to mark the cleanup function that runs when the module is removed.

The Linux kernel module loader calls the init function when a module is loaded and calls the exit function when the module is removed. 
These functions are registered using module_init() and module_exit() macros.

5. what is copy_to_user / copy_from_user explain the complete flow

copy_to_user() and copy_from_user() are kernel functions used to safely transfer data between kernel space and user space. 
copy_from_user() copies data from user space to kernel space, while copy_to_user() copies data from kernel space to user space.
Direct access between these spaces is not allowed for security and stability reasons.


User Application
       ↓
write() system call
       ↓
VFS (Virtual File System)
       ↓
Driver write() function
       ↓
copy_from_user()
       ↓
Kernel buffer

use-space calls: 
write(fd, "hello", 5);

kernel driver function called:
ssize_t my_write(struct file *file,
                 const char __user *buf,
                 size_t len,
                 loff_t *off)
{
    char kbuf[100];
    copy_from_user(kbuf, buf, len);
    printk("Data from user: %s", kbuf);
    return len;
}

6. what is copy-on-write 

Copy-on-Write (COW) is a memory management technique where multiple processes share the same memory pages until one process modifies the data, 
at which point the operating system creates a separate copy of the page.

fork() called
      ↓
Parent & Child share memory
      ↓
Pages marked read-only
      ↓
Process attempts write
      ↓
Page fault triggered
      ↓
Kernel copies the page
      ↓
Process writes to new page

