8. how can we request I/O memory in the user space ? explain with coding

In Linux, user-space programs normally cannot directly access I/O memory (device registers) because it is protected by the kernel.
However, it can be accessed by mapping the device’s physical I/O memory into user space using mmap().

This is commonly used in memory-mapped I/O (MMIO).

#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <sys/mman.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdint.h>

#define DEVICE_ADDR 0x40000000
#define MAP_SIZE 4096

int main()
{
    int fd;
    void *map_base;
    volatile uint32_t *reg;

    fd = open("/dev/mem", O_RDWR | O_SYNC);
    if (fd < 0)
    {
        perror("open");
        return -1;
    }

    map_base = mmap(NULL,
                    MAP_SIZE,
                    PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE,
                    MAP_SHARED,
                    fd,
                    DEVICE_ADDR);

    if (map_base == MAP_FAILED)
    {
        perror("mmap");
        return -1;
    }

    reg = (volatile uint32_t *)map_base;
    printf("Register value: %x\n", *reg);
    *reg = 0x1;   // write to device register
    munmap(map_base, MAP_SIZE);
    close(fd);
    return 0;
}

9. Difference between ioremap and mmap 

ioremap() is a kernel function used by device drivers to map physical device memory into kernel virtual address space, 
while mmap() is a system call used in user space to map files or device memory into a process's virtual address space.


Feature	                ioremap()	                                                mmap()
Space	                Kernel space	                                            User space
Purpose	                Map physical device I/O memory → kernel virtual address	    Map file/device memory → user virtual address
Used in	                Device drivers	                                            User applications
Defined in	            Linux kernel	                                            POSIX system call
Returns	                Kernel virtual address	                                    User virtual address

10. How remap_pfn_range() works

remap_pfn_range() is a Linux kernel function used in a driver’s mmap() implementation to map physical memory pages (device memory) 
into a user process's virtual address space by creating appropriate page table entries.

remap_pfn_range() is a Linux kernel function used in device drivers to map physical memory pages into user space virtual memory.
It is typically used inside the driver’s mmap() file operation.

This allows a user-space program to directly access device memory (MMIO or DMA buffers).

User Virtual Memory
        │
        │ mmap()
        ▼
Kernel Driver
        │
 remap_pfn_range()
        ▼
Device Physical Memory


10. what are different modes to communicate between user space and kernel space

In Linux, communication between User Space and Kernel Space happens through several mechanisms. 
These mechanisms allow user programs to request services or exchange data with the kernel or device drivers.

syscal/ioctl/proc/sysfs/mmap

The main mechanisms for communication between user space and kernel space in Linux are system calls, 
ioctl, procfs, sysfs, netlink sockets, memory mapping (mmap), signals, and device file interfaces.

11. why do we use copy_to_user instead of memcpy

copy_to_user() is used instead of memcpy() because it safely copies data from kernel space to user space by validating 
the user memory and handling page faults, while memcpy() does not perform these checks and can crash the kernel.


